<div class='main'>

			<div class='running-text'>
			<p><b>Urban-Nurture</b></p>
			<p><i>Rethinking where our FOOD comes from...and where our WASTE goes</i></p>
			<p><b>Date</b> 2010<br/>
			<b>Location</b> Varies<br/>
			<b>Size</b> 320 and 80 sq. ft. depending on container</p>
				
			<p>Many countries import far more than they export, resulting in a surplus of shipping containers. Urban-Nurture reuses shipping containers to provide an integrated, off-the-grid, closed-loop cycle that addresses the need for local, fresh, and affordable produce. It also provides a use for human waste, which becomes a stimulant for growth in the surrounding landscape. Food and waste modules develop a symbiotic relationship with nature in the form of a food market and park. The system is also scalable for a site's specific needs. Urban-Nurture evolved during a collaborative studio made possible through a federal grant that aimed to stimulate jobs in Rhode Island. The aquaponics module was my design while the waste module was designed by Cheryle Cranbourne. </p>
			</div>
			
